    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Trea Turner** (72.23) and **Yordan Alvarez** (68.04) anchoring the lineup, representing our highest efficiency plays against Pfaadt and Castillo, respectively. **Trea Turner** is the focal point of our stolen base strategy today; despite a neutral platoon, Pfaadt\u2019s slow delivery gives **Trea Turner** a significant runway to exploit the basepaths, a critical component given our organizational emphasis on SB scarcity. **Kyle Schwarber** (65.95) also commands a premium spot, benefiting from an elite xwOBA and favorable park factors that elevate his score well above his base projection. While **Junior Caminero** (50.56) and **Caleb Durbin** (50.76) remain in the lineup, they sit on the lower end of our efficiency threshold, primarily hampered by tougher SP matchups against Fried and Leahy that necessitate a disciplined approach to our daily game cap management.\n\nThe most difficult exclusion today was **Carson Benge** (39.27), who fell just shy of our 40.0 floor. His profile was decimated by a L/L platoon disadvantage against Lopez, which pushed him into bench territory despite a respectable base projection. Meanwhile, **Victor Scott II** (35.34) remains a high-variance asset who unfortunately draws an elite hold pitcher in Suarez, further suppressing his stolen base upside and relegating him to the bench. We are tracking a major risk with **Christian Yelich** (40.19), whose score is precariously close to the floor due to a tough matchup against Griffin (2.70 xERA); if he shows any signs of early-game struggle, we will look to rotate bench depth to preserve our cap. We continue to monitor the status of **Kazuma Okamoto** and **Zac Veen**, the latter of whom remains stashed in the minors, while **Lars Nootbaar**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, and **Luis Pena** remain sidelined or unavailable for today\u2019s tactical rotation.",
